FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - KAZAKHSTAN: OIE CONFIRMED
************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
See Also
Foot & mouth disease - Kazakhstan (Karaganda) 20010513.0926
Foot & mouth disease - Kyrgyzstan 20010307.0471
Foot & mouth disease - Kazakhstan: OIE report 20000615.0964
Foot & mouth disease - Kyrgyzia (Bishkek) 20000526.0841
Date: 9 Jun 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/a_current.htm>

See also: 28 Jul 2000, 30 Jun 2000, 9 Jun 2000
(Date of last previously reported outbreak: June 2000)
Emergency report: Translation of a fax received on 4 Jun 2001 from Dr Sh.
Zh. Tursunkulov, President, Veterinary Surveillance Committee, Ministry of
Agriculture, Astana:
Report date: 23 May 2001.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 5 May 2001.
Estimated date of first infection: 2 May 2001.
Outbreaks: No. of outbreaks 1
Location: Mirny settlement in the Osakarovka district of the Karaganda
Oblast (Central
Kazakhstan).
Description of affected population: cattle in the private sector.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
species susceptible cases deaths destroyed slaughtered
bov 574 3 0 3 0
ovi 197 0 0 0 0
sui 150 0 0 0 0
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: National Veterinary Laboratory,
Astana.
B. Diagnostic tests used: serological tests (immunodiffusion, complement
fixation and precipitation) to detect the presence of foot and mouth
disease (FMD) virus antibodies, and biological tests on lesion samples.
C. Causal agent: FMD virus subtype O1.
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: under investigation.
B. Other epidemiological details: the susceptible cattle population has not
been vaccinated against FMD for 30 years.
Control measures:
- A report has been sent to the services concerned.
- Quarantine has been declared in Mirny settlement and in the zone at risk
(within a radius of 30 km) in Osakarovka district, under which the entry,
exit and transit of commodities subject to veterinary inspection are
forbidden.
- Vaccination of susceptible animals in the outbreak and in the zone at risk.
- Cleaning and disinfecting of affected farms.
- Sick cattle are euthanised and their carcasses destroyed by incineration.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Kazakhstan is located directly north of Kyrgyzstan but this does not
appear to be transmission across their common border as the outbreak is
located in the central part of the country. Note that ProMED-mail reported
this outbreak almost 4 weeks ago. - Mod.PC
